        <title><m>\S 5.1</m>: LU Factorization (Solutions)</title>
            <page>
                <exercise workspace="2in">
                    <title>Motivation: LU Factorization</title>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <solution>
                        <p>
                            Recall that applications of linear algebra typically involve computation with very large 
                            matrices. In these final sections, we'll re-visit two old concepts to illustrate creative methods
                            for how these computations can be done practically.
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                </exercise>

            
            
                <exercise workspace="4in">
                    <title>Example: LU Factorization</title>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            Let <m>A = \left[\begin{array}{rrr}
1 \amp 2 \amp 1 \\
2 \amp 0 \amp -2 \\
-1 \amp 2 \amp -1 \\
\end{array}\right]</m>.

                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <solution>
                        <p>
                            This is revisiting <url href="https://jshriner6.github.io/math369-FA2025/notes/sec-3-1-2-sols.html#sec-3-1-2-sols-3-1">the Gaussian Elimination and Matrix Multiplication activity</url>
                            from section 3.1.
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                    
                </exercise>
     </page>
            <page>
                <exercise>
                    <title>Using LU Factorization to Solve Systems</title>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            Use the LU Factorization of <m>A</m> to solve <m>A\xvec=\bvec</m> when 
                            <m>\bvec = \threevec123</m>.
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <solution>
                        <p>
                            We can solve <m>A\xvec=\bvec</m> by solving two simpler equations:
                            <ol>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        <m>L\cvec = \bvec</m>
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        <m>U\xvec = \cvec</m>
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                            </ol>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            The first requires forward substitution, in which we find <m>\cvec = \threevec104</m>.
                            The second requires backward substitution, in which we find <m>\xvec= \threevec01{-1}</m>, 
                            which gives us our final answer.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Note that once we have the LU factorization, we can solve <m>A\xvec=\bvec</m> for any <m>\bvec</m>
                            quickly just by using substitution.
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                    
                </exercise>
            </page>
            <page>
                <exercise>
                    <title>Practice: LU Factorization and Solving Systems</title>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            Find an LU Factorization for <m>A = \left[\begin{array}{rrr}
2 \amp -3 \amp 1 \\
-4 \amp 5 \amp 0 \\
2 \amp -2 \amp 2 \\
\end{array}\right]</m>. Use it to solve <m>A\xvec = \bvec</m> when
                                <ol>
                                    <li>
                                        <p>
                                            <m>\bvec = \threevec8{-13}8</m>
                                        </p>
                                    </li>
                                    <li>
                                        <p>
                                            <m>\bvec = \threevec{-1}{0}3</m>
                                        </p>
                                    </li>
                                </ol>
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <solution>
                        <p>
                            The LU factorization for <m>A</m> is given in <url href="https://understandinglinearalgebra.org/sec-gaussian-revisited.html#example-LU">Example 5.1.1</url>,
                            as is the solution to the first system. For the second system, we should compute that 
                            <m>\cvec = \threevec{-1}{-2}2</m> and <m>\xvec=\threevec{25/6}{10/3}{2/3}</m>.
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                    
                </exercise>
            </page>
            <page>
                <exercise>
                    <title>Remark</title>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            We only get <m>A=LU</m> when we don't permute rows as part of Gaussian elimination. In 
                            general, we can write <m>PA = LU</m>, where <m>P</m> is a <term>permutation matrix</term> which
                            has information regarding row permutations, and use this to solve systems similarly.
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    
                </exercise>
            </page>

